1 Introduction

The diet is called the “Mimic Fasting Diet” -> http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/science-news/11683736/Five-day-fasting-diet-slows-down-ageing-and-may-add-years-to-life.html.

Apparently, fasting has a lot of benefits. In addition to losing weight, fasting can slow the aging process and reduce the risk of some age-related diseases like cancer and diabetes.

So this is the structure of the diet plan: Reduce calorie intake for five days each month and eat food that is comprised of:

Day 1 :: 1090 calories

  • Protein - 10% of the calories
  • Fat - 56% calories
  • Carbs - 34% calories

Days 2 - 5 :: 725 calories

  • Protein - 9%
  • Fat - 44%
  • Carbs - 47%

Data source is the USDA Nutrition database from the USDA web site http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/doc/index.

Names of the columns and the descriptions of the columns are listed here: http://www.ars.usda.gov/sp2UserFiles/Place/80400525/Data/SR27/sr27_doc.pdf

2.2 Food

This file contains long and short descriptions and food group designators for all food items, along with common names, manufacturer name, scientific name, percentage and description of refuse, and factors used for calculating protein and kilocalories, if applicable. Items used in the FNDDS are also identified by value of “Y” in the Survey field.

##   NDB_No FdGrp_Cd                  Long_Desc                Shrt_Desc ManufacName
## 1   1001      100             Butter, salted         BUTTER,WITH SALT        <NA>
## 2   1002      100 Butter, whipped, with salt BUTTER,WHIPPED,WITH SALT        <NA>
## 3   1003      100      Butter oil, anhydrous     BUTTER OIL,ANHYDROUS        <NA>
## 4   1004      100               Cheese, blue              CHEESE,BLUE        <NA>
## 5   1005      100              Cheese, brick             CHEESE,BRICK        <NA>
## 6   1006      100               Cheese, brie              CHEESE,BRIE        <NA>

Column descriptions

NDB_No : 5-digit Nutrient Databank number that uniquely identifies a food item. If this field is defined as numeric, the leading zero will be lost.
FdGrp_Cd : 4-digit code indicating food group to which a food item belongs.
Long_Desc : 200-character description of food item.
Shrt_Desc : 60-character abbreviated description of food item. Generated from the 200-character description using abbreviations in Appendix A. If short description is longer than 60 characters, additional abbreviations are made.

There are 8,618 rows in the data set.

Pay attention!!! The following 4 entries in the Shrt_Desc that are doubles:

##                                                      Shrt_Desc
## 1                                         BABYFOOD,MEAT,BF,STR
## 2 BEEF,CHUCK,UNDER BLADE CNTR STEAK,BNLESS,DENVER CUT,LN,0" FA
## 3     OIL,INDUSTRIAL,PALM KERNEL (HYDROGENATED),CONFECTION FAT
## 4                                     POPCORN,OIL-POPPED,LOFAT

So it is recommended to use the long descriptions in the future. In addition they are better for the undestanding.

2.2.1 Reduce the food data set

Originally there are 8,618 rows in the food data set.

Remove the foods that are from the 4 food groups that are not necessary for this project and were removed earlier from the food group data set. After this procedure there are 7,612 rows in the food data set.

2.4 Nutrient

This file contains the nutrient values and information about the values, including expanded statistical information.

A nutrient is anything that nourishes a living being. We humans get our nutrients from what we eat, plants get theirs from the soil. While the best nutrients are natural, we can also get them from vitamins in a bottle. Organic nutrients consist of carbohydrates, fats, proteins.
Source: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nutrient

##   NDB_No Nutr_No Nutr_Val
## 1   1001     203     0.85
## 2   1001     204    81.11
## 3   1001     205     0.06
## 4   1001     207     2.11
## 5   1001     208   717.00
## 6   1001     221     0.00

There are 654,572 entries in the nutrient data set.

Column descriptions

NDB_No : 5-digit Nutrient Databank number that uniquely identifies a food item.
Nutr_No : Unique 3-digit identifier code for a nutrient.
Nutr_Val : Amount in 100 grams, edible portion.

There are 150 unique nutrient values in the data set. Which should be the same as the number of entries in the nutrient definition data set.

Class of each column

## $NDB_No
## [1] "integer"
## 
## $Nutr_No
## [1] "integer"

## $Nutr_Val

2.4.1 Reduce the size of nutrient data set

By limiting the nutrients data set to the only for this project necessary nutrients (Carbs, fat, protein and calories) the number of entries in the nutrient data set has been decreased to 34,472. This smaller nutrient data set will make the join easier.

We can notice that the nutrient value is very skewed. Let’s look at the histogram. For better visualisation the x axis has been limited.

Even thought the maximum value is 902 for the nutrient value, there are 70% data between 0 and 40.

2.5 Weight

This file contains the weight in grams of a number of common measures for each food item.

##   NDB_No Seq Amount              Msre_Desc Gm_Wgt
## 1   1001   1      1 pat (1" sq, 1/3" high)    5.0
## 2   1001   2      1                   tbsp   14.2
## 3   1001   3      1                    cup  227.0
## 4   1001   4      1                  stick  113.0
## 5   1002   1      1 pat (1" sq, 1/3" high)    3.8
## 6   1002   2      1                   tbsp    9.4

There are 15,228 entries in the weight data set. And there are 1,917 unique entries int he measure description (Msre_Desc) column.

Column descriptions

NDB_No : 5-digit Nutrient Databank number.
Seq : Sequence number.
Amount : Unit modifier (for example, 1 in “1 cup”).
Msre_Desc : Description (for example, cup, diced, and 1-inch pieces).
Gm_Wgt : Gram weight.

Class of each column

3 Join the data sets

All the data sets together:

##     data_set number_of_rows
## 1       food          7,612
## 2 food_group             21
## 3   nutrient          8,618
## 4     weight         15,228

After joining all the data sets the final data set has 13,688 rows.

13,581 (out from the orginal 15,228) entries in the weight data set are matched to the food data set. The rest of the entries were not matched because part of the food entries have been removed as they are not relevant for this project.

In addition there are more entries in the new joined data frame than in the matched weight data set because there are some foods (NDB_No) who don’t have an entry in the weight data set. There are 107 such foods.
